<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="72.[700,1229,193,333]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific epithet is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[819,939,281,304]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangulus">
<emphasis box="[819,939,281,304]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">triangulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(having three angles). I refer to the trigonal shape of the pygidium.
</paragraph>
